{"ts": "2026-06-09T16:34:23.480761+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Here's how the app bootstraps, renders layouts, and loads the About page:\n\n---\n\n## 1. App Bootstrap (`src/main.js`)\n\nThe entry point is `src/main.js`. It does the following in order:\n\n1. **Creates the Vue app** from the root `App.vue` component.\n2. **Globally registers** the `Default` layout component under the name `LayoutDefault` (`app.component('LayoutDefault', Default)`). This makes it available by name throughout the app without explicit imports.\n3. **Installs Pinia** (the state management store).\n4. **Installs the Vue Router** (the `router` instance exported from `src/router/index.js`).\n5. **Mounts** the app onto the `#app` DOM element.\n\n## 2. Routing Setup (`src/router/index.js`)\n\nThe router is created with **hash-mode history** (`createWebHashHistory()`), meaning URLs look like `/#/`, `/#/about`, etc.\n\nTwo routes are defined:\n\n| Path | Name | Component | Layout Meta |\n|------|------|-----------|-------------|\n| `/` | `Home` | Eagerly imported `Home.vue` | `'default'` |\n| `/about` | `About` | **Lazy-loaded** via dynamic `import()` | `'default'` |\n\nBoth routes set `meta.layout` to `'default'`. Note: a developer comment in the file claims all routes are eagerly loaded, but the code itself uses a dynamic `import()` for the About route — so in reality, **the About page is code-split into a separate chunk**.\n\n## 3. Layout Rendering (`src/App.vue`)\n\n`App.vue` is the root component rendered inside `<div id=\"app\">`. Its template is:\n\n```html\n<component :is=\"layout\">\n  <RouterView />\n</component>\n```\n\nThe `layout` computed property reads `this.$route.meta.layout` (falling back to `'default'`) and prefixes it with `layout-`, producing the string `layout-default`. Because `main.js` globally registered the Default layout component as `LayoutDefault`, Vue resolves the dynamic `<component :is=\"layout\">` to that component.\n\nSo the rendering chain is:\n\n```\n<div id=\"app\">\n  └─ <LayoutDefault>           ← wraps the page in nav + footer\n       ├─ <DefaultNav />\n       ├─ <RouterView />       ← renders the matched route's view component\n       └─ <DefaultFooter />\n  └─ </LayoutDefault>\n```\n\nThe **Default layout** (`src/layouts/default/Default.vue`) itself is a simple wrapper with a sticky-footer pattern: it renders `<DefaultNav />`, a `<slot />` (where `<RouterView />` is projected in), and `<DefaultFooter />`.\n\n## 4. How the About Page Loads\n\nWhen a user navigates to `/#/about`:\n\n1. Vue Router matches the `/about` route.\n2. Because the component is defined as `() => import('../views/About.vue')`, the router **lazy-loads** the `About.vue` chunk from the server on first visit. On subsequent visits it's cached.\n3. `App.vue` computes `layout` → `'layout-default'`, so the `<component :is=\"layout\">` renders the Default layout.\n4. `<RouterView />` injects the loaded `About.vue` into the layout's `<slot />`.\n5. `About.vue` itself is minimal — it renders a `<div class=\"container\"><h1>This is the about page</h1></div>`, wrapped by the nav and footer from the layout.\n\nIn summary: **the app uses a global layout pattern driven by route `meta.layout`**, and the **About page is lazy-loaded via dynamic import** and rendered inside the Default layout shell.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 833, "prompt_tokens": 14534, "total_tokens": 15367, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": null, "reasoning_tokens": 29, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": null, "cached_tokens": 12864}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "mimo-v2.5-pro", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "81e25107850c4e368da3f09494356c6f", "finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ead3b-ca37-7510-a54d-5c3ec65ec8